#import libraries for stock data
import pandas as pd
import pandas_datareader as pdr
import datetime
from collections import OrderedDict
In [2]:
#10 year data we're going to scrape
def create_df():
    d = OrderedDict()
    start = datetime.datetime(2008,12,31)
    end = datetime.datetime(2018,12,31)

    #pull stock prices for 10 years of data from 2008 to 2018
    for tk in ['BK', 'STT', 'JPM', 'C', 'NTRS']:
        d[tk] = pdr.DataReader(tk, "yahoo", start, end)
        d[tk]['Symbol'] = tk
        d[tk] = d[tk].reset_index().set_index(['Date', 'Symbol'])
    
    df = pd.concat([d[key] for key in d], axis=0)
    df = df.sort_index(axis=0, level=0)

    return df
df = create_df()

  • Adjusted Price: Is the most accurate, since it's the true price, once accounting for corporate events:

    • New offerings: Corporation offer additional shares of stock
    • Stock splits: Individual stock becomes too expensive and splits the stock increasing the shares, but decreasing the price
    • Dividends: Payouts to shareholders in the form of cash, or shares; this good for stockholders, but reduces the stocks price

  • JPM is 53, NTRS is 59 and STT is 56 adj_close price on average is in upper 50s; with NTRS, the adj_close at 59

  • C open price is 45, while BK is lowest of low at 32
Stocks Compared to One Another Conclusion:¶
  • Open, High, low and close is representative of trading on a daily basis, but the adj_close is ultimately the mose accurate price due the the fact it's adjusted for corporate actions after the fact
  • Volume shows the number of shares traded of a stock or the availabiltiy of the stock in the market
  • The theory is that when price and volume move together; the stock is "acting" correctly

Candlestick Plots and Simple Moving Average¶
  • Candlestick plot is better suited for daily trading than 10 year plot, so you can see and interpret the bars better
  • The red indicates price is in downward trend and green indicates the price is in an upward trend (candlestick patterns are a little more complicated than that, but for analysis purposes will focus on upward and downward price movements
  • The 50-day and 200-day MAs are widely followed by investors and traders, with breaks above and below this moving average considered to be important trading signals
  • 50 day moving average and 200 day moving follow a similar pattern, but obviously the 200 day moving average has more lag and is more smoothed out
  • A bullish sign is when the 50 day moving average rises above the 200 day moving average (bullish sign)
  • A bearish sign is when the 50 day moving average drops below the 200 day moving average (bearish sign)

def BK_AdjClose_Volume():
    #create subplots side by side
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(22,6))


    plt.ticklabel_format(style = 'plain')

    #Adj_Close price/Volume plots side by side
    sns.lineplot(x='Date', y='Adj_Close', color='Blue',
                 data=df_BK, ax=ax[0]).set_title('10 year Adjusted BNY Mellon Close Price')

    sns.lineplot(x='Date', y='Volume', color='Darkblue', 
                 data=df_BK, ax=ax[1]).set_title('10 year Volume Traded of BNY Mellon Stock')
    
    return plt.show()
BK_AdjClose_Volume()
  • The large volume movements earlier are probably representative of the recession which started in December 2007 and ended in June 2009; the effects seemed to linger until 2012
  • The stock price followed this trend too reaching its lowest point
  • After 2012, the stock price has been on a steady rise with a slight dip in 2016 and a recent dip in 2018; however, trading volume seems relatively steady the last 4 years
  • The stock price and trading volume seem to follow a similar pattern daily especially with level trading volume the last 5 years
  • Average volume over 10 years 7,122,123
  • Average stock price over 10 years 32.59

def BK_Candlestick():

  • Since, these are banks and they're in a the same sector they tend to follow the same pattern and probably have a fairly strong correlation

  • Price movements have a risen after the recession, but volume seems quite level after this period; in particular, in the past 5 years

#10 year data including S&P 500 for BETA analysis
def create_BETA():
    start = datetime.datetime(2008,12,31)
    end = datetime.datetime(2018,12,31)
    
    symbols = ['BK','STT', 'C','JPM', 'NTRS', '^GSPC']
    
    for tk in symbols:
        df_BETA = pdr.DataReader(symbols, "yahoo", start, end)['Adj Close']
        
    return df_BETA
df_BETA = create_BETA()

def linereg_BK():

#scipy linear regression
import scipy.stats as st

def scip_BK():
    slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = st.linregress(return_SP500, return_BK)

    print('Alpha or Y intercept: ', '{:f}'.format(intercept))
    print('Beta or slope: ', '{:f}'.format(slope))
    print('R-Squared: ', '{:f}'.format(r_value**2))
    print('p-value: ', '{:f}'.format(p_value))
    print('standard error:' , '{:f}'.format(std_err))
    
    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(16, 10))

    ax = sns.regplot(x='^GSPC', y='BK', ax=ax,
                     data=returns)

    text = 'y = -0.000174 + 1.419291x'
    leg = ax.legend(loc='best', bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 0., 0.5, 0.5), fontsize = 'large',labels="")
    leg.set_title(text, prop = {'size':'x-large'})
    plt.title('10 Year Correlation Between BNY Mellon Stock Price and SP500 Index Price')
    plt.xlabel('SP500 (%) change')
    plt.ylabel('BK (%) Change')
    plt.show;
    
    return
scip_BK()

Hypothesis Testing and Confidence Intervals¶

$$Definitions\ of\ Notation\ Used:$$ $$H_O: Null\ Hypothesis$$ $$H_1: Alternative\ Hypothesis$$ $$\mu_{_s}: Stock\ Return\ population \ mean$$ $$\mu_{_i}: Index\ Return\ population\ mean$$ $$\alpha: level\ of\ significance\ 5\%$$ $$P: P-Value$$

Two Tailed Test¶
  • Are the stocks returns the same as the index return?

$$Mathematical\ Statement:$$ $$H_0: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} = 0$$ $$H_1: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} \neq 0$$

One Tailed Tests¶

Lower or Left Tailed Test¶
  • Are the stock's returns less than the index?

$$Mathematical\ Statement:$$ $$H_0: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} \geq 0$$ $$H_1: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} \ < 0$$

Upper or Right Tailed Test¶
  • Are the stock's returns greater than the index?

$$Mathematical\ Statement:$$ $$H_0: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} \leq 0$$ $$H_1: \mu_{_s} - \mu_{_i} \ > 0$$

Probablity Value and Significance Level¶

$$Mathematical\ Statement:$$ $$H_0: P \geq \alpha$$ $$H_1: P \ < \alpha$$

import researchpy as rp

def tt_BK():
    #results of population percentage change between stk/idx price data
    des, res = rp.ttest(returns['BK'], returns['^GSPC'],
                            paired= True)

    print(des, '\n')
    print(res, '\n')
    
    #critical t for significance level of .05 and degree of freedom of 2516 (n-1)
    tcritical = st.distributions.t.ppf(1-.05/2,2516)
    print('critical t: %.5f' % tcritical)
    
    #t-statistic and p-value for a paired two tailed test
    paired_sample = st.ttest_rel(returns['BK'], returns['^GSPC'])
    print('t-statistic: %.5f,  two tailed p-value: %.5f'% paired_sample)
    
    return

def data_BK():
    #sampling distribution for difference in means to check for normality in the data for testing
    np.random.seed(42)
    sample_data = returns.sample(252)

    stk_price, idx_price, price_diffs = [],[],[]

    for _ in range(10000):
        price_diffs_sample = sample_data.sample(252, replace=True)
        stk_price_mean = price_diffs_sample['BK'].mean()
        idx_price_mean = price_diffs_sample['^GSPC'].mean()
        stk_price.append(stk_price_mean)
        idx_price.append(idx_price_mean)
        price_diffs.append(stk_price_mean - idx_price_mean)
        
    #confidence interval/standard deviation/means for the sampling distribution for difference in means
    print('Sample Confidence Interval for Difference in Means: %.5f'% np.percentile(price_diffs, 2.5), 
          '%.5f' % np.percentile(price_diffs, 97.5),'\n')
    print('Sample Mean: %.5f'% np.mean(price_diffs),'\n')
    print('Sample Std Deviation: %.5f'% np.std(price_diffs))
    
    #plotted histogram of price_diffs
    plt.hist(price_diffs, alpha = 0.5, label='price_diffs');
    plt.title('Sampling Distribution for Difference in Means')
    plt.xlabel('Difference in Mean for BK and SP500', fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize = 14)
    plt.legend(fontsize = 14);
    
    return

def data_JPM():
    #sampling distribution for difference in means to check for normality in the data for testing
    np.random.seed(42)
    sample_data = returns.sample(252)

    stk_price, idx_price, price_diffs = [],[],[]

    for _ in range(10000):
        price_diffs_sample = sample_data.sample(252, replace=True)
        stk_price_mean = price_diffs_sample['JPM'].mean()
        idx_price_mean = price_diffs_sample['^GSPC'].mean()
        stk_price.append(stk_price_mean)
        idx_price.append(idx_price_mean)
        price_diffs.append(stk_price_mean - idx_price_mean)
        
    #confidence interval/standard deviation/means for the sampling distribution for difference in means
    print('Sample Confidence Interval for Difference in Means: %.5f'% np.percentile(price_diffs, 2.5), 
          '%.5f' % np.percentile(price_diffs, 97.5),'\n')
    print('Sample Mean: %.5f'% np.mean(price_diffs),'\n')
    print('Sample Std Deviation: %.5f'% np.std(price_diffs))
    
    #plotted histogram of price_diffs
    plt.hist(price_diffs, alpha = 0.5, label='price_diffs');
    plt.title('Sampling Distribution for Difference in Means')
    plt.xlabel('Difference in Mean for JPM and SP500', fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylabel('Count', fontsize = 14)
    plt.legend(fontsize = 14);
    
    return

def tt_NTRS():
    #results of population percentage change between stk/idx price data
    des, res = rp.ttest(returns['NTRS'], returns['^GSPC'],
                            paired= True)

    print(des, '\n')
    print(res, '\n')
    
    #critical t for significance level of .05 and degree of freedom of 2516 (n-1)
    tcritical = st.distributions.t.ppf(1-.05/2,2516)
    print('critical t: %.5f' % tcritical)
    
    #t-statistic and p-value for a paired two tailed test
    paired_sample = st.ttest_rel(returns['NTRS'], returns['^GSPC'])
    print('t-statistic: %.5f,  two tailed p-value: %.5f'% paired_sample)
    
    return
